metadata.name: Gensuzendō #33
metadata.description:
Gensuzendō - Generative Calligraphy
By Frank Force @KilledByAPixel

Hitsuzendō 筆禅道 "way of Zen through brush" is believed by Zen Buddhists to be a method of achieving nirvana. This work is my own way of following that practice.

Features ancient, modern, inverse, and graffiti styles.
Stamps are also generated with many varieties possible.
Right click to save a 2048x2048 image.

Programmed in JavaScript
By Frank Force @KilledByAPixel

Based on my tiny calligraphy generator... https://www.dwitter.net/d/22709

with(x)t?lineWidth=t%5:(scale(9,9),d=Date.now(),fillStyle=R(d%400)),C(a=t+d|stroke())>.9|t>9?beginPath(fillText(String.fromCharCode(d%5e5),129,99)):lineTo(99+4*(z=6*C(t*9*C(a)))*S(a+d),8+t*11+z)

metadata.name: Shattered Obelisks #41
metadata.description:
Shattered Obelisks began as a work that is dedicated to my habit of mindlessly drawing on paper when I am stressed, depressed or immersed in difficult thoughts.

Like a patient undergoing psychotherapy and piecing together the causes of unconscious fears and anxieties, I and my artwork have assembled ourselves into something shaped, found order in the chaos and separated it from the external noise.

It took 3 months of continuous, obsessive work. I have developed a huge library, designed for hand-like drawing. The functionality of this library is four times larger than what is shown in this drop.

I plan to put this library out into the public domain when I deem it complete, and hope that it will help someone express themselves through the creative process as much as it helped for me.

In case you've encountered a problem with inverted colours, try changing browser or disabling extensions. This problem only occurred once during testing on a massive amount of devices and was resolved by disabling extensions.

IMPORTANT NOTES BLOCK:

NOTE 1: This artwork should be viewed at a browser scale of 100%. Reducing the scale will increase the amount of detail, but may unpredictably affect the preservation of the location of secondary objects.

NOTE 2: This work can be printed on a plotter. Click S for saving it in .SVG.
Detailed instructions and answers to possible questions can be found in the console output of the code.

NOTE 3: This drop is the first one from the series of 3. It will be used as AL ticket in next drops of this series.

@abakshonokoleg
01.08.2022
Tech: P5.JS

metadata.name: Ersbla #564
metadata.description:
Ersbla is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022. 

It is the third entry in a series of abstract generative experiments inspired by the graphic and textile work of Anni and Josef Albers. As a follow-up to the 'Sabler' and 'Lebras' collections, 'Ersbla' produces textile effects using a combination of thousands of tiny dots arranged on variable grids, resulting in a wide variety of unique Bauhaus-inspired compositions in a variety of palettes.

Press 'S' to save a high-resolution 2400 x 3396 px image in PNG format.

Depending on the density of your output, please allow up to a few seconds for your edition to generate.

metadata.name: Stateful Parameters #27
metadata.description:
Stateful Parameters is part of the fxhackathon 2023: co-creation interfaces.

Use the custom minting interface to set up the starting state for the grid. Clicking on a glyph will cycle it through each character in the alphabet. Clicking and drag to edit characters faster. Blank characters do not animate.

Press 'c' to set the whole canvas to blank characters.
Once minted, press 'd' to download a .gif version of your work.

The custom interface provides a new way for collectors to interact with finite-state-machines and other similar projects by setting a starting state themselves.

objkt.name: 晩夏の山岳 Mountains in Late Summer #58

metadata.name: 晩夏の山岳 Mountains in Late Summer #58
metadata.description:
晩夏の山岳 Mountains in Late Summer 
is the third and final piece in the summer series of 2023, following "初夏の旅路 Traveling in Early Summer" and "真夏の花火 Fireworks in Midsummer".

Throughout the summer series, I have tried to depict some of the landscapes or unforgettable memories that I encountered during the summer in Japan. This time, "Mountains in Late Summer" is no exception. Trying to depict mountains using codes. Also, I used the same particle system for the whole summer series, and this time I used the same particle system for the depiction and rolling of the mountains that I used in the previous two works. In addition, glsl is still used this time to add morphological changes to the mountains. In fact, these mountains are all depicted by the basic ellipse function with gradient color and glsl. I hope you can like the mountains I depicted.

----・----・----

created using p5.js and glsl

----・----・----

Save as a Picture:

Press “s”or “S” to download a PNG copy of the artwork.

metadata.name: XSkull #32
metadata.description:
XSkulls: Myths Unveiled”

XSkulls are constructed with 7 visual layers. The background is generated generatively, while the subsequent 6 layers, which are digitally handcrafted designs, overlay it. This collection's background falls into four categories: solid color, gradient, pattern, and animated. Each is generated using code.

💾 Press 'S' to save the PNG image of the current view.

🅿️5️⃣ Built with p5.js
📑Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0
🔆 This is a generative art collaboration with Arash and Shahrokh.
